Ummmmm...okaaaayyy. o_O

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Why do we enjoy it so?
">

I actually don't enjoy it as much as I used to but, when it was broadcast
during the 80s, it took a more mature and imaginative approach than the
farmed-out 'american animation' that was available at the time.  Even in
its edited form, Star Blazers/Space Cruiser Yamato was a breath of fresh
air.

Series and OAVs like Ranma 1/2, Mario M-66, (Demon Prince) Zenki and,
yes, ecchi series like Ultimate Girls have kept the spirit alive while
snorefests like a certain 'X' movie and Drag-on Brawl ZZZZZZ have
threatened to topple the towers, so to speak.

(Something tells the saying about how '90% of everything is crap' applies
even here) 9_9

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What do we enjoy most about anime?
">

Four words: Smoothness, story, risk-taking.

Compared to the childish nature of series like Inspector Gadget and Stunt
Dawgs, the anime I saw took a more 'mature' approach than most -
characters bled, suffered and died, women weren't always whiny victims
and the stories, particularly in Robotech/Macross eps, were cleverly
written if not epic in scope.

In fact, the only 'american' films and shorts I've seen that appear to
match or surpass those classics have been made/supervised by Timm/Dini
(Batman:TAS, Justice League, Batman Beyond), Brad Bird (the Family Dog
pilot), Ralph Bakshi (Spicy City, Wizards), Glenn Eichler (Daria) and
John Kricfalusi (the original Ren and Stimpy) and that should tell you
something about what's currently being tolerated by the current crop of
networks/viewers. 9_9

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is there a particular stereotype of anime enthusiast?
">

If there is, I probably don't fit it, so to speak.

If people enjoy animation, whether it was made 'in-house' or farmed out,
why should those viewers be branded?

Animation, as a tool/medium, can entertain as well as educate.  It all
depends on who's guiding the pencil(s)/pixels/typewriter keys.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What draws us into the world so fervently?
">

There are several factors I could mention but I'll just say 'atmosphere'
and leave it at that. ~_^

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What is our favorite show?  Why?
">

I actually listed a few favorites up above but I'd be happy to go into
more detail. ^_^

Daria won my heart because of its wide variety of characters and the
acidic wit of its titular character and her friend.  Then again, being
well written didn't hurt either. ~_^

Batman: the Animated Series caught my eye because it offered a fresh
approach to DC's characters.  They were 'deeper' than the ones portrayed
in the cornball 'Adam West' vehicle and the fact that villains were
tragic victims of their oftentimes cruel world made us feel sorry for
them...almost.

Family Dog, when first introduced via the sci-fi series 'Amazing
Stories', added some much-needed grit to a medium almost destroyed by
WB's Bugs Bunny 'Specials'.

And Ren and Stimpy, well...was just plain funny. (before Sick-elodeon
fired their creator but that's ancient history)

I could wax poetic about how Spawn fanned the bat-flames and Zenki mixed
'fetishitic themes' with 'girl power' but I think you get the idea. ^_^

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is there anything else you would like to add?
">

Just a 'paraphrase' to stir the pot - although it's wonderful that the
various studios are (taking a shot at) catering to their young audiance,
sooner or later, these viewers have to grow up and one can only hope that
the studios/networks will grow with them.  While fart jokes and bad
dialogue may appeal to some people, IMO, they're only the tip of the
iceberg.  There are a lot of brilliant and powerful stories one can tell
and dozens (if not hundreds) of paths one could explore all within the
prime-time/late-night time slots.

All one has to do is that that first (or is that fifth?) simple step...

*the writer feels the sole of a naked geisha's foot sink into his back*
*he shrieks in display of half-agony that quickly turns to exstacy*

Aaaah, that's the spot.

*the geisha bends down to give her customer a kiss on the cheek*

(Okay, I'm exagerating, but you get my point) }:^)

Signed,
Warewolf
who has also pencilled in a viewing of Robot Chicken.
