Starting from the top...

My favorite artistic medium is animation.  I mean, its got the big
draws of the motion picture (sound, music, and moving visuals),
except you don't have to depend on live sets or actors, but just
on whatever you can draw on the page.  You can literally create
any world you want.  Some of the most fascinating fictional
locales are animation.  the Third Earth of Thundercats for example.

Animation, of course, also allows you to break the rules a bit.
A show like Dragonball for example, simply wouldn't work in
live-action without looking dorky, as anyone who has seen a
Hong Kong action flick can tell you.

But, well, I live in America, and America really kind of wastes
the potential of the medium.  The last really mature, imaginative,
and well-written cartoon to come out of America was Filmation's
Bravestarr (I know some people would say the various DCAU
shows would count as well, but I'm not one of those people).
Other than that, most of the animation I would consider truly
good or great comes from out of the country.

Usually, from Japan.

Why Japan?  Well because, most other countries tend to
see animation the same way America does:  As being
primarily a repository for crappy humor shows, not as a
medium that can do action and drama.  Japan is the exact
opposite--they will, literally, do anything as a cartoon if they
think it'll make them some money.  So you get a diversity
of animation choices that really doesn't exist anywhere else.

In America, nowadays all you can get are lame cynical
humor shows like Billy and Mandy, or superheroes like
Ben 10 or the endless DC/Marvel tie-ins.  But Japan is
different.  Want an animated soap opera?  Japan's got it.
Want a show entirely about the everyday school life of an
average kid?  It happens.  I want to see an action story
where the hero actually DOESN'T win?  It happens.  And
as we all know, want to see an anime where mean and
terrible things are done to women of all ages (and sometimes,
species)?  Its out there.

And what's more, while Japan will compromise storytelling
for profits (like the case with Shaman King) they usually
still retain the best parts--anime and manga universes
are malleable, they change and evolve as things go on.

I know some anime is stagnant too, but most of it, or at
least most of the ones I'm watching, certainly aren't.
I've been watching Dragonball recently and its a good
case in point:  Goku trains his tail to not be his weakness
anymore (then has it cut off so he won't transform),
most of his enemies either die permanently or reform
and become good guys.  Instead of fighting the same
battles over and over, the Z-Fighters are always facing
new challenges (except Buu, who was kind of a
retread of Cell) and moving on to bigger and better
things.

Meanwhile, Batman is still fighting the diabolical plans
of the Penguin, still falling for the same n00bish &quot;OMG
someone snuck up behind me and knocked me out&quot;
traps that he's been falling for since the 1960s even
though he's supposed to be a super-sensitive trained-in-the
-arts-of-ninjutsu vigilante, still getting perplexed by the
same Riddler conundrums that he's been getting
perplexed by for a million years.  And all the while,
he catches the villains only for them to be free again
in the next episode, having made no notable change in
their mentality, personality, or tactics... or if they do
change, its only for one episode and they go back to
being bad again in the next one.  Sometimes they
even degrade from their original state--Mad Hatter
for example was originally motivated by love and
jealousy, but by the third boxed set he's just another
greedy bank robber (and--not to knock the tastes of
people who like this show--but THIS is everyone's
idea of &quot;mature storytelling&quot; with &quot;dynamic characters?&quot;)

Now, of course there are American cartoons that
don't suck, either because they lack that killer
stagnancy or because they have some other
quality that more than makes up for it.  Those
rare cartoons usually run a chance of standing
side-to-side with the best anime in my opinion.
However those kinds of cartoons are rarely made
here and there hasn't really been a great one in
almost eight years.  Anime however, even though
the discovery of the international market has forced
some dumbing-down on it, has yet to lose the
vital qualities of diversity and malleability.
